    <item>
      <title>Bash $PATH filtering</title>
      <link>https://purpleidea.com/blog/2024/03/02/bash-path-filtering/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 02 Mar 2024 19:54:00 -0500</pubDate>
      <guid>https://purpleidea.com/blog/2024/03/02/bash-path-filtering/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;As most modern GNU+Linux distro users already know, you get a lot of &lt;a href=&#34;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU&#34;&gt;tools&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;included for free! Many of these may clutter up your &lt;code&gt;$PATH&lt;/code&gt; and make &lt;code&gt;bash&lt;/code&gt; tab&#xA;completion more difficult than it has to be. Here&amp;rsquo;s a way to improve this!&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;text-decoration:underline; font-weight: bold;&#34;&gt;A mess&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s what I see when I tab-complete &lt;code&gt;cd&amp;lt;TAB&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#f8f8f8;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;james@computer:~$ &lt;span style=&#34;color:#a2f&#34;&gt;cd&lt;/span&gt;&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#a2f&#34;&gt;cd&lt;/span&gt;                 cddb_query         cd-info            cd-read&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;cd-convert         cd-drive           cd-it8             cdrecord&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;cd-create-profile  cd-fix-profile     cdmkdir            cdtmpmkdir&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;cdda-player        cd-iccdump         cd-paranoia&#xA;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;I genuinely only use three of those commands.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
